<!-- Section header / intro card --><div style="border:1px solid #e8eef6;border-radius:16px;background:#fbfdff;padding:18px 18px 16px 18px;">
<div style="font-size:13px;font-weight:800;color:#5b6b88;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px;">Asset Information Requirements</div>
<div style="border:1px solid #e8eef6;border-radius:14px;background:#ffffff;padding:14px 16px;margin-top:10px;">
<div style="font-size:14px;font-weight:900;color:#0e1e3d;margin-bottom:6px;">Identifying maintainable assets</div>
<div style="color:#1c2430;line-height:1.6;font-size:14px;">Before defining what information is required, it is essential to agree on which assets need to be managed once the building is in operation.</div>
</div>
<div style="color:#5b6b88;line-height:1.65;font-size:14px;margin-top:12px;">Not every element within a model requires ongoing tracking or structured data. The focus here is on assets that will be operated, maintained, inspected, or monitored after handover.</div>
<div style="color:#5b6b88;line-height:1.65;font-size:14px;margin-top:10px;">Maintainable assets typically include those that require planned maintenance, carry warranties or performance criteria, influence safety or comfort, or need to be tracked within operational systems such as CAFM, BMS, or a digital twin.</div>
</div>
